.TH CMT_DLL 3 "LIBCMT" "CMT_DLL" "Dynamic Link Library Handling"

.SH NAME
CMT_DLL \- Cross-platform dynamic link library functions

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #define INCL__DLL
.br
.B #include <LIBCMT/LIBCMT.h>

.SH FILES
LIBCMT/FUNCTIONS/DLL.h

.SH DESCRIPTION
Provides macros and typedefs for handling dynamic link libraries (DLLs) across different platforms.

.TP
.B DLL, dll
Typedef for a variable representing an opened DLL.

.TP
.B OPEN_DLL, open_dll()
Open a DLL file.

.TP
.B READ_DLL, read_dll()
Retrieve a function pointer from the DLL.

.TP
.B CLOSE_DLL, close_dll()
Close a DLL file.

.TP
.B DYNAMIC, dynamic
Mark a function or variable as dynamically linkable.

.SH USAGE
Create a DLL:
.nf
#include <stdio.h>

void dynamic my_write(void) {
    printf("TEST\n");
}
.fi

Compile:
.nf
gcc -c my_dll.c -o my_dll.o
gcc -shared my_dll.o -o my_dll.dll
.fi

Connect and call function:
.nf
dll dll_file;
dll_file = open_dll("my_dll.dll");

void (*my_write)();
my_write = (void (*)()) read_dll(dll_file, "my_write");

my_write();
close_dll(dll_file);
.fi

.SH NOTES
- Ensure the DLL is open before calling functions from it to avoid segmentation faults.
- OS/2 16-bit or AmigaOS-3 may require retrieving functions by ordinal number.
- This system abstracts cross-platform DLL keywords and function access.

